<h3>Common Challenges Related to Compiling Clinical Information Requirements and a Data Dictionary</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Starting with a large set of “important” data needs/elements, rather than focusing on the needs for each prioritized Use Cases.</li>
  <li>Not thinking aobut how maximize the utility of information across other potential Use Cases.  For example, the group may be working on information needed for initial diagnosis of cancer, but could also think ahead about other potential uses of that same information and how slight changes to their initial requirements might make that same information for, say, clinical trials matching, conducting trials, etc. </li>
  <li>Asking for interpreted information rather than source data because that is established practice.  A trivial example would be asking for age, rather than collecting birth data and date/time of the encounter. </li>
<li> [NOTE: more to be added]

<p>These and other potential pitfalls can be largely avoided by following the <%= link_to("Design Principles", "/playbook/design_principles.html") %> compiled based on CodeX and mCODE experience, and available from a link on the left.</p>
</ul>

<h3>Clinical Review of the Data Dictionary</h3>
<ul>
