<h3>Terminologies</h3>
<p>As noted before, terminologies, standard clinical code systems, are important for unambiguously defining how data within the data element are represented.  When a term cannot be found within an existing code system, it’s possible to work with the owner of the code system to add new terms, provided the justification is convincing.</p>


<h3>Questions to Plan FHIR IG development</h3>
<ul>
<li>What are the possibly-related, external FHIR IG initiatives?
  <ul>
<li>Are there projects being driven by others in Government and/or industry that need to be reviewed, consulted, and/or partnered with?</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li>What FHIR resources and profiles best fit the data model? 
<ul>
	<li>What resources and profiles best match the required data elements in the data model?</li>
	<li>What resources and profiles result in the fewest FHIR extensions that are needed</li>
	<li>Leveraging the defined purpose of resources and profiles that match desired use in implementation guide</li>
	<li>What FHIR resources and profiles allow the necessary terminologies</li>
	<li>Selected FHIR resources and profiles do not require data elements that may not be present in an exchange</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li>What FHIR profiles are needed? Profiles are created when further specifications (extensions or constraints) are needed on a FHIR base resource or an existing dependent FHIR profile.
