<h3>Maintaining HL7 Standards</h3>
<p>Once the first version of a specialty standards (Standard for Trial Use or STU) has been completed and published, work begins on maintaining the standard over time. Any standard that is valued, implemented into systems, used widely will generate requests for updated versions.</p>
<p>Updates to speciality standardards maybe needed for a variety of reasons. The  standards on which your standard depend (e.g., FHIR) may be updated, and may or may not require or at least motivate changes to standards that depend on them. Users may ask vendors who've integrated your standard or the vendors themselves may ask for updates. Governement rules and regulations may motivate changes.</p>
<p>Because changes to your standard may be required over time, it's important to keep a core of the original standards team intact (and add to that core), with the necessary skills (e.g., clinical, FHIR, HL7) availble when needed. It's important to keep a good relationship with the sponsoring Work Group. It's necessary to have a system to collect, organize, prioritize, and address requests for changes and other comments - likely the same system used for building the original standard (e.g, Jira at HL7).</p>
<p>Be aware that the interest of the original team, and even of the Use Case Champions, may change as the work enters maintenance. As repeatedly emphasized in this Playbook, think about which members of the Community care most about ensuring a standard is maintained in a well-governed, careful manner. For example, vendors who've implemented the standard and provided it to many customers typically care about maintenance.</p>
<p> ... etc.</p>

<h3>Best Practices for Smoother HL7 Standardization,Based on the CodeX/mCODE Experience</h3>
<ul>
<li>The standards process leader for the Use Case should have thorough knowledge of HL7 processes and standardization schedule.</li>
<li>Build HL7 standardization into your Use Case plan from the start.  Allow plenty of time to go through the process.</li>
<li>Have a good relationship with a sponsoring HL7 Work Group and its leadership. Ensure they are included in plans and progress, and respect that your IG is usually not the only IG the Work Group is reponsible for. They likely won't have deep expertise in your health specialty (though, it's possible they do.  However, they will know HL7 standards (including FHIR), HL7 processes, and work that other Work Groups are doing that may related to your work.
<li>Conducting the Use Case project within (or near) an HL7 FHIR Accelerator (CodeX or other) has the benefit of working within an organization that will be more knowledgeable of and more closely connected to HL7 people and processes.</li>
